Step 1 — Create a Resource Group

First, create a resource group to organize all resources related to the VPN lab.

Navigate to:

Azure Portal → Resource Groups → Create

Configuration:

Resource Group Name: RG-Azure-VPN-Lab
Region: Canada Central

Click Review + Create, then Create.

Step 2 — Create the Virtual Network

Next, create a Virtual Network that will host internal resources.

Navigate to:

Azure Portal → Virtual Networks → Create

Configuration:

Name: VNet-VPN-Lab
Region: Canada Central
Address Space: 10.1.0.0/16
Subnet Name: default
Subnet Address Range: 10.1.1.0/24

Click Review + Create, then Create.

Step 3 — Create the Gateway Subnet

A VPN Gateway requires a dedicated subnet called GatewaySubnet.

Navigate to:

Virtual Network → Subnets → Add

Configuration:

Subnet Name: GatewaySubnet
Address Range: 10.1.255.0/27

Save the configuration.

Step 4 — Create a Public IP Address

The VPN Gateway requires a public IP address to allow remote connections.

Navigate to:

Azure Portal → Public IP Addresses → Create

Configuration:

Name: VPNGateway-PublicIP
SKU: Standard
Assignment: Static
Region: Canada Central

Step 5 — Deploy the VPN Gateway

Now create the Azure VPN Gateway that will handle secure VPN connections.

Navigate to:

Azure Portal → Virtual Network Gateway → Create

Configuration:

Name: VPNGateway-Lab
Region: Canada Central
Gateway Type: VPN
VPN Type: Route-Based
SKU: VpnGw1
Generation: Generation1
Virtual Network: VNet-VPN-Lab
Public IP Address: VPNGateway-PublicIP

Click Review + Create, then Create.

Step 6 — Configure Point-to-Site VPN

After the VPN Gateway has been deployed, configure the Point-to-Site VPN settings.

Navigate to:

VPN Gateway → Point-to-site configuration

Configuration:

Address Pool: 172.16.0.0/24
Tunnel Type: OpenVPN (SSL)
Authentication Type: Azure Certificate

Click Save.

This address pool will assign IP addresses to VPN clients connecting to the network.


Step 7 — Generate VPN Client Configuration

Once the P2S configuration is saved, download the VPN client package.

Navigate to:

VPN Gateway → Point-to-site configuration

Click:

Download VPN Client

This downloads a ZIP file containing:

VPN client configuration

certificates

connection profile

Step 8 — Install VPN Client on Local Machine

Install the OpenVPN client on the local computer.

Steps:

Extract the downloaded VPN client package

Locate the OpenVPN configuration file

Import the profile into the OpenVPN client

This configures the local device to connect securely to the Azure VPN Gateway.

Step 9 — Connect to the VPN

Open the VPN client and initiate the connection.

Once connected:

The client receives an IP address from the 172.16.0.0/24 pool

The machine becomes logically part of the Azure Virtual Network

Step 10 — Verify Connectivity

To verify the VPN connection, run the following tests.

Check Assigned VPN IP

Run:

ipconfig

Look for the VPN adapter and confirm an IP address has been assigned.

Test Connectivity to Azure Resources

Example:

ping 10.1.1.4

If successful, the remote client can now communicate securely with internal Azure resources.
